{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CjNBEq4PdzNatyza3LrJYa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting - the ES logs directory only shows GC logs, not JSON logs. This means the ES logging might be going to stdout/stderr rather than a log file. In containerized ES, by default, ES logs to stdout (for containers) rather than to files.\n\nLet me check if there's a logging configuration or if ES logs are going to stdout.\n\nActually, in Elasticsearch Docker images, by default (since 7.x), the logging goes to stdout. The `path.logs` is set but logs can also go to stdout. Let me check the ES logs more carefully.\n\nSince ES logs are going to stdout in the container, Filebeat should use the `container` log input type to collect from container stdout/stderr rather than from the filesystem log files. \n\nThe challenge is that reading from container stdout in a sidecar setup is more involved—I'd need to access the node's filesystem or the Docker/containerd log files. A simpler approach would be to configure Elasticsearch to write to log files in a shared volume that Filebeat can read from, or have Filebeat read directly from the container's log file on the host node. I could configure Elasticsearch to write logs to a shared volume that Filebeat can read from, or use Filebeat's container input type to read directly from the host node's container logs. Let me explore which approach works best for this setup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4442,"cache_read_input_tokens":33888,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4442},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7620048d-b302-467c-8c03-e7259111ff8c","uuid":"67522760-2704-48a9-bb2c-5d84ac087010