{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HnQg5GoAFf58EjLxwnnj1X","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"ES is running and healthy. But Metricbeat is getting \"connection refused\" on port 9200 on localhost. This is odd because the ES container is healthy. Let me check if ES is listening on localhost within the pod network.\n\nWait, actually looking at the Metricbeat error more carefully:\n- `dial tcp 127.0.0.1:9200: connect: connection refused`\n- `dial tcp [::1]:9200: connect: connection refused`\n\nThese are trying to connect to `localhost:9200`. But the ES container IS listening on port 9200 (we just verified it's healthy). \nSince Metricbeat and Elasticsearch are in the same pod, they share the network namespace and should both see localhost. The problem might be that Elasticsearch just restarted 96 seconds ago and hasn't fully initialized yet, even though the container shows as Running and the readiness probe passed. I verified ES is responding to curl, so it should be accepting connections.\n\nBut wait—Metricbeat is still getting connection refused errors. Looking at the timestamps more carefully, those error logs are from the initial startup phase around 22:46-22:47, which was before Elasticsearch fully came online. I need to check the most recent Metricbeat logs to see if the connection issues have actually resolved.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":764,"cache_read_input_tokens":68690,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":764},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7620048d-b302-467c-8c03-e7259111ff8c","uuid":"220eba30-5591-45fe-b892-e86c7905abda","request_id":"req_011CcM1LhjXUcM3frZiAK3rQ"}
